n be eaten to counteract enchantments.\n* [[John Milton]] referred to \"...that Moly/That Hermes once to wise Ulysses gave\" in lines 636 and 637 of the ''Mask Performed at Ludlow Castle'', also known as [[Comus]]. See https://www.dartmouth.edu/~milton/reading_room/comus/text.shtml.\n* In [[Ursula K. Le Guin]]'s, [[The Farthest Shore]], the true names of the moly plant are taught to students of Roke, \u201cNow the petal of the flower of moly hath a name, which is iebera, and so also the sepal, which is partonath; and stem and leaf and root hath each his name...\"\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|24em}}\n\n== References ==\n*{{Citation | last = Homer | author-link = Homer | last2 = Butler | first2 = Samuel | author2-link = Samuel Butler (novelist) | title = The Odyssey | year = 1898 | volume = [[wikisource:The Odyssey (Butler)/Book X|Book X]] | url = http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Odyssey_(Butler)}}\n\n;Attribution\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Moly |volume=18 |page=681}}\n\n{{Greek religion|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Greek mythology]]\n[[Category:Mythological plants]]\n", "name_user": "ShadowInTheMoonlight", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moly_(herb)"}
